{"title_page": "Arirang", "text_new": "{{short description|Korean folk song}}\n{{About|the Korean traditional song}}\n{{Infobox intangible heritage\n| Image       = [[File:North Korea Victory Day 274 (9524347338).jpg|250px]]\n| Caption     = A man about to depart on a journey through a mountain pass is seen off by a woman in a scene from the [[Arirang Festival]] in [[North Korea]].\n| ICH         = Arirang in North Korea\n| State Party = North Korea\n| Type        = \n| Criteria    = \n| ID          = 914\n| Region      = APA\n| Year        = 2014\n| Session     = 9th\n| Danger      = \n| Link        = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/lists?RL=00914\n| Below       = \n| Note        = \n}}\n{{Infobox intangible heritage\n| Image       = [[File:Song So-Hee performing Arirang.jpg|250px]]\n| Caption     = [[Song So-hee]] performing \"Arirang\"\n| ICH         = Arirang in South Korea\n| State Party = South Korea\n| Type        = \n| Criteria    = \n| ID          = 445\n| Region      = APA\n| Year        = 2012\n| Session     = 7th\n| Danger      = \n| Link        = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/lists?RL=00445\n| Below       = \n| Note        = \n}}\n\n\"'''Arirang'''\" ({{lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791}}; {{IPA-ko|a.\u027ei.\u027ea\u014b|}}) is a [[Koreans|Korean]] [[Folk music|folk song]] that is often considered to be the [[anthem]] of [[Korea]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2014/11/27/39/0701000000AEN20141127000300315F.html|title=N. Korea's Arirang wins UNESCO intangible heritage status|date=2014-11-27|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206005934/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2014/11/27/39/0701000000AEN20141127000300315F.html|archive-date=2017-12-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> There are about 3,600 variations of 60 different versions of the song, all of which include a refrain similar to, \"Arirang, arirang, arariyo ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694}})\"<ref name=\":2\" /> It is estimated the song is more than 600 years old.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/03/317_126329.html|title='Arirang' makes it to UNESCO heritage|last=Chung|first=Ah-young|date=2012-12-12|newspaper=The Korea Times|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n\"Arirang\" is included twice on the [[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] list. [[South Korea]] successfully submitted the song for inclusion on the UNESCO list in 2012.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?lg=en&pg=00011&RL=00445|title=Arirang, lyrical folk song in the Republic of Korea|work=Intangible Cultural Heritage|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref> [[North Korea]] also successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?lg=en&pg=00011&RL=00914|title=Arirang folk song in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|website=Intangible Cultural Heritage|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref> In 2015, the [[South Korea]]n [[Cultural Heritage Administration]] added the song to its list of important intangible cultural assets.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/07/15/2015071501147.html|title='Arirang' Listed as National Intangible Asset|date=2015-07-15|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe song is sung today in both North and South Korea, a symbol of unity in an otherwise divided country, since the Korean war.\n\n==History==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2017}}\n\n===Origin===\nIt is believed that \"Arirang\" originated in [[Jeongseon County|Jeongseon]], [[Gangwon Province, South Korea|Gangwon Province]]. According to a legend, the name is derived from the story of a bachelor and a maiden who fell in love while picking [[Camellia]] blossoms near the wharf at Auraji ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\uc6b0\ub77c\uc9c0}}). There are two versions of this story. In the first one, the bachelor cannot cross the Auraji to meet the maiden because the water is too high and so, they sing a song to express their sorrow. In the second version, the bachelor attempts to cross the Auraji and drowns, singing the sorrowful song after he dies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DsR3BgAAQBAJ|title=Encyclopedia of Korean Folk Literature|last=The National Folk Museum of Korea|publisher=\uae38\uc7a1\uc774\ubbf8\ub514\uc5b4|year=2014|isbn=978-8928900848|volume=Encyclopedia of Korean Folklore and Traditional Culture Vol. III|location=|pages=95\u201396}}</ref>\n\nOther theories on the origin of the name \"Arirang\" point to [[Lady Aryeong]], wife of the first king of [[Silla]]; \"arin,\" the [[Jurchen language|Jurchen]] word for \"hometown\".\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/08/135_126317.html|title=From lyrical folk song to cheering song: variations of 'Arirang' in Korean history|date=2012-12-06|work=The Korea Times|access-date=2017-12-06|agency=Yonhap News Agency|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to {{nowrap|Prof. Keith Howard}}, \"Arirang\" originated in the mountainous regions of [[Jeongseon]] and the first mention of the song was found in a 1756 manuscript.<ref name=\"Howard2017\">{{cite book|author=Keith Howard|title=Perspectives on Korean Music: Preserving Korean Music: Intangible Cultural Properties as Icons of Identity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LgskDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT108|date=15 May 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-91168-9|volume=I}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Pete Seeger, who sang the song in concert in the 1960s, the song goes back to the 1600s when a despotic emperor was imprisoning people right and left who had opposed him. He hung these prisoners from tall pine trees on top of the hill of Arirang, located outside Seoul. Legend states that one of the prisoners condemned to death, walked his final miles singing of how much he loved his country, and how much he hated to say goodbye to it. It was soon picked up by the other prisoners, where it became a Korean tradition that any man had the right to sing this song before his execution.\n\n===First recording===\nThe first known recording of \"Arirang\" was made in 1896 by American [[Ethnology|ethnologist]] [[Alice Cunningham Fletcher|Alice C. Fletcher]]. At her home in [[Washington, D.C.]], Fletcher recorded three Korean students singing a song she called \"Love Song: Ar-ra-rang.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170927000618|title=Oldest recorded Arirang to be on display in Seoul|last=Yoon|first=Min-sik|date=2017-09-27|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2012/05/04/25/0701000000AEN20120504002500315F.HTML|title=Arirang under renewed light ahead of UNESCO application|last=Kim|first=Hyeh-won|date=2012-05-11|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> One source suggests that the students belonged to noble Korean families and were studying abroad at [[Howard University]] during the period in which the recording was made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ikorea.ac.kr/File/intro/Fletcherpreliminaryarticle.pdf|title=Alice Fletcher's Notes on the Earliest Recordings of Korean Music|last=Provine|first=Robert C.|work=The Academy of Korean Studies|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> The recordings are currently housed in the U.S. [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lccn.loc.gov/2015655305|title=Alice C Fletcher collection of Korean cylinder recordings|website=Library of Congress|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n===Resistance anthem===\nDuring the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese occupation of Korea]] from 1910 to 1945, when singing was proscribed and it became a criminal offense for anyone to be singing any patriotic song including the national anthem of Korea, Arirang became an unofficial anthem. \"Arirang\" became a resistance anthem against [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] rule.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Atkins|first=E. Taylor|date=August 2007|title=The Dual Career of \"Arirang\": The Korean Resistance Anthem That Became a Japanese Pop Hit|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=66|issue=3|pages=645\u2013687|lay-url=|jstor=20203201|doi=10.1017/s0021911807000927|url=http://commons.lib.niu.edu/handle/10843/13185}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WhZRCgAAQBAJ&dq|title=Traditional Music: Sounds in Harmony with Nature|last=Koehler|first=Robert|publisher=Seoul Selection|year=2015|isbn=978-1624120428|series=Volume 8 of Korea Essentials|location=|pages=}}</ref> Korean protesters sang \"Arirang\" during the [[March 1st Movement|March 1 Movement]], a Korean demonstration against the Japanese Empire in 1919. Many of the variations of \"Arirang\" that were written during the occupation contain themes of injustice, the plight of labourers, and guerrilla warfare. It was also sung by the mountain guerrillas who were fighting against the fascists. <ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe most well-known lyrics to \"Arirang\" first appeared in the 1926 [[silent film]] ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]],'' directed by [[Na Woon-gyu]]. ''Arirang'' is now considered a [[lost film]] but various accounts say the film was about a Korean student who became mentally ill after being imprisoned and tortured by the Japanese. The film was a hit upon its release and is considered the first Korean nationalist film.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Film Out of Bounds: Essays and Interviews on Non-Mainstream Cinema Worldwide|last=Edwards|first=Matthew|publisher=McFarland|year=2014|isbn=978-1476607801|location=|pages=198}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Divine Work, Japanese Colonial Cinema and its Legacy|last=Taylor-Jones|first=Kate|publisher=Bloomsbury USA|year=2017|isbn=978-1501306136|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity in Japan===\nDuring the Japanese occupation of Korea, Japan experienced a craze for Korean culture and for \"Arirang\", in particular. Over 50 Japanese versions of \"Arirang\" were released between 1931 and 1943, in genres including [[Pop music|pop]], [[jazz]], and [[Mambo (music)|mambo]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Some of the former Japanese Imperial soldiers remember and sing \"Arirang\" from the memories they recollect from their service in [[Japanese Korea]], or from the Korean [[comfort women]] (sex slaves) or the Korean forcefully-inscripted labourers and soldiers.\n\n===Musical score===\n<score vorbis=\"1\">\n\\relative c' { \\key f \\major \\time 9/8 \\tempo \"Lento\" 4 = 140 \\set Staff.midiInstrument = #\"violin\"\nc4. ~ c4 d8  c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4. g8 a g f4 ( d8 ) | c4. ~ ( c4 d8 c d ) r8 |\\break\nf4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4 ( g8 ) f4 ( d8 ) c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8 f4.| f4. ~ f4. r4. |\\break\nc'4. ~ c c | c4. a4. g4. | a4. g4 a8 f4 ( d8 ) | c4. ~ ( c4  d8 c d ) r8 |\\break\nf4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4 ( g8 ) f4 ( d8 ) c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8 f4.| f4. ~ f4. r4. \\bar \"|.\"}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\ub098 \ub97c \ubc84 \ub9ac \uace0 \uac00 \uc2dc \ub294 \ub2d8 \uc740\n\uc2ed \ub9ac \ub3c4 \ubabb \uac00 \uc11c \ubc1c \ubcd1 \ub09c \ub2e4}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\uccad \ucc9c \ud558 \ub298 \uc5d4 \ubcc4 \ub3c4 - \ub9ce \uace0\n\uc6b0 \ub9ac \ub124 \uac00 \uc2b4 \uc5d4 \uafc8 \ub3c4 \ub9ce \ub2e4}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\uc800 \uae30 \uc800 \uc0b0 \uc774 \ubc31 \ub450 \uc0b0 \uc774\ub77c \uc9c0\n\ub3d9 \uc9c0 \uc123 \ub2ec \uc5d0 \ub3c4 \uaf43 \ub9cc \ud540 \ub2e4}\n</score>\n\n==Lyrics==\nAll versions of \"Arirang\" include a [[refrain]] similar to, \"Arirang, arirang, arariyo ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694}}).\"<ref name=\":2\" /> The word \"arirang\" itself is nonsensical and does not have a precise meaning in [[Korean language|Korean]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/arirang.php|title=Arirang (\uc544\ub9ac\ub791)|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> While the other lyrics vary from version to version, the themes of sorrow, separation, reunion, and love appear in most versions.<ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQkyBgAAQBAJ|title=Two Lenses on the Korean Ethos: Key Cultural Concepts and Their Appearance in Cinema|last=Kim Yoon|first=Keumsil|last2=Williams|first2=Bruce|publisher=McFarland|year=2015|isbn=978-0786496822|location=|pages=39}}</ref>\n\nThe table below includes the lyrics of \"Standard Arirang\" from [[Seoul]]. The first two lines are the refrain. The refrain is followed by three [[Verse (music)|verses]].\n\n{|\n|\n: '''Korean'''\n|\n: '''Romanization'''\n|\n: '''English translation'''<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Damodaran|first=Ramu|date=Winter 2017|title=UNAI Impacts Scholarship, Research for Greater Good|url=|journal=SangSaeng|publisher=APCEIU|volume=49|pages=23|via=}}</ref>\n|-\n|\n: \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694...\n: \uc544\ub9ac\ub791 \uace0\uac1c\ub85c \ub118\uc5b4\uac04\ub2e4.\n|\n: Arirang, Arirang, Arariyo...\n: Arirang gogaero neomeoganda.\n|\n: Arirang, Arirang, Arariyo...\n: You are going over Arirang hill.\n|-\n|\n: \ub098\ub97c \ubc84\ub9ac\uace0 \uac00\uc2dc\ub294 \ub2d8\uc740\n: \uc2ed\ub9ac\ub3c4 \ubabb\uac00\uc11c \ubc1c\ubcd1\ub09c\ub2e4.\n|\n: Nareul beorigo gasineun nimeun\n: Sibrido mosgaseo balbyeongnanda.\n|\n: My love, you are leaving me\n: Your feet will be sore before you go ten [[Li (unit)|''ri'']].\n|-\n|\n: \uccad\ucc9c\ud558\ub298\uc5d4 \uc794\ubcc4\ub3c4 \ub9ce\uace0,\n: \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub124 \uac00\uc2b4\uc5d4 \ud76c\ub9dd\ub3c4 \ub9ce\ub2e4.\n|\n: Cheongcheonhaneuren janbyeoldo manko,\n: Urine gaseumen huimangdo manda.\n|\n: Just as there are many stars in the clear sky,\n: There are also many dreams in our heart.\n|-\n|\n: \uc800\uae30 \uc800 \uc0b0\uc774 \ubc31\ub450\uc0b0\uc774\ub77c\uc9c0,\n: \ub3d9\uc9c0 \uc123\ub2ec\uc5d0\ub3c4 \uaf43\ub9cc \ud540\ub2e4.\n|\n: Jeogi jeo sani Baekdusaniraji,\n: Dongji seotdaredo kkotman pinda.\n|\n: There, over there, that mountain is [[Baekdu Mountain]],\n: Where, even in the middle of winter days, flowers bloom.\n|}\n\n==Variations==\nThere are an estimated 3,600 variations of 60 different versions of \"Arirang.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Titles of different versions of \"Arirang\" are usually prefixed by their place of origin.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWhile \"[[Jeongseon County|Jeongseon]] Arirang\" is generally considered to be the original version of the song, \"Bonjo Arirang\" (literally: Standard Arirang) from [[Seoul]] is one of the most famous versions. This version was first made popular when it was used as the theme song of the influential 1926 film ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOther famous variations include \"Jindo Arirang\" from [[South Jeolla]] Province, a region known for being the birthplace of Korean folk music genres [[pansori]] and [[sinawi]]; and \"[[Miryang]] Arirang\" from [[South Gyeongsang]] Province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/jindo.php|title=Jindo Arirang|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/milyang.php|title=Milyang Arirang|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Official status==\n[[File:Arirang (USAS).ogg|thumb|right|Arirang performed by the [[United States Army Band]] Strings with a tenor soloist]]\n\n===UNESCO===\nBoth [[South Korea]] and [[North Korea]] submitted \"Arirang\" to be included on the [[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] list. South Korea successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2012.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> North Korea successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\" />\n\n===South Korea===\nIn 2015, the South Korean [[Cultural Heritage Administration]] added the \"Arirang\" to its list of important intangible cultural assets.<ref name=\":5\" />[[File:Arirang.ogg|thumb|right|Arirang performed by the [[United States Army Band]] Chorus with a tenor soloist]]\n\n===U.S. Army===\n[[File:Arirang,_Lyrics_in_English_Adaptation-2_by_GSIT_at_HUFS_in_2013,_sung_by_HUFS_students.ogg|thumb|right|Arirang, Lyrics in English Adaptation-2 by GSIT at HUFS in 2013. Adaptation of [[W. B. Yeats]]' poem, \"The Falling of the Leaves,\" into the Arirang melody to convey the woe and sorrow with which Korean people sympathize when listening to the song.]]\nThe [[United States Army|U.S. Army's]] [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]] adopted \"Arirang\" as its official march song in May 1956, after receiving permission from [[Syngman Rhee]], the first president of South Korea. The division had been stationed in Korea from 1950 to 1953, during the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.7ida.us/history.asp|title=Chronological History 7th Infantry Division|date=2012-05-25|website=7th Infantry Division Association|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|section|date=October 2018}}\n\n===Music===\n* American composer [[John Barnes Chance]] based his 1962-63 [[concert band]] composition ''[[Variations on a Korean Folk Song]]'' on a version of \"Arirang\" that he heard in Korea in the late 1950s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teaching Music Through Performing in Band Volume 1|last=Blocher, Cramer, Migliaro Corporon, Lautzenheiser, Lisk, Miles|publisher=GIA Publications, Inc.|year=2010|isbn=|location=Chicago|pages=590\u2013598}}</ref>\n\nPete Seeger sang the song, with an English translation in a concert in the 1960s.\n\n* The tune of \"Arirang\" is used for the 1986 Christian hymn, \"Christ, You Are the Fullness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hymnary.org/text/christ_you_are_the_fullness|title=Christ, You Are the Fullness|website=Hymnary|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n* The [[New York Philharmonic]] performed \"Arirang\" for an encore during [[2008 New York Philharmonic visit to North Korea|its trip to North Korea]] on February 26, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/world/asia/27symphony.html|title=North Koreans Welcome Symphonic Diplomacy|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=2008-02-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* In November 2013, the student choir at [[Hankuk University of Foreign Studies]] performed \"Arirang\" in English, Chinese, Japanese, French, Italian, Spanish, German, Russian, Arabic and Korean.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20131119001011|title=HUFS to hold concert featuring 'Arirang' in 10 languages|last=Lee|first=Claire|date=2013-11-19|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[K-pop]] group [[BTS (band)|BTS]] performed an \"Arirang\" medley at [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] France in June 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Mnet K-POP|title=[KCON 2016 France\u00d7M COUNTDOWN] Opening Performance _ Arirang Medley(\uc544\ub9ac\ub791 \uc5f0\uace1) M COUNTDOWN 160614 EP.47|date=2016-06-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vwc5zTayVJw|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref>\n* An October 2016 episode of South Korean TV music competition show ''[[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend]]'' was an \"Arirang\" special, featuring famous musicians performing different variations of the song.<ref>{{Citation|last=KBS World TV|title=Immortal Songs 2 {{!}} \ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1 2: \"Arirang\" special [ENG/2016.10.29]|date=2016-10-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vXVwekhWne0|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref>\n* On June 12, 2018, a Slovenian avant-garde music group [[Laibach]] marked the historic summit in [[Singapore]] between President [[Donald Trump]] and the leader of [[North Korea]], [[Kim Jong-un]], by sharing a track dedicated to the  [[Korean reunification]] process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w_PCdJ3Dn9E|title=Laibach - Arirang (Official Audio)|last=YouTube|date=2018-06-12|work=Mute Records|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\n* ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]]'' is the title of early Korean filmmaker [[Na Woon-gyu]]'s influential 1926 film, which popularized the song \"Arirang\" in the 20th century.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''[[Arirang (2011 film)|Arirang]]'' is also the title of a 2011 South Korean documentary. The film won the top prize in the [[Un Certain Regard]] category at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jun/07/arirang-review|title=Arirang \u2013 review|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=2012-06-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n* [[Arirang (TV network)|Arirang TV]] and [[Arirang Radio]] are international English-language media stations run by the [[Korea International Broadcasting Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2011/04/113_86027.html|title=Arirang TV begins DTV service in metropolitan Washington, D.C., area|date=2011-04-28|work=The Korea Times|access-date=2017-12-08|agency=Yonhap News Agency|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/01/11/2012011101582.html|title=Arirang Radio to Go On Air in U.S.|date=2012-01-11|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en}}</ref>\n* Arirang will appear in the [[Gardens by the Bay]] Musical Lighting in [[Singapore]].\n\n===Sports===\n* North Korea's mass gymnastics and performance festival is commonly known as the [[Arirang Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2013/07/pyongyangs-arirang-festival-eye-candy-for-the-masses/|title=Pyongyang's Arirang Festival: Eye Candy for the Masses|last=DeHart|first=Jonathan|date=2013-07-29|work=The Diplomat|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* At the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]], South Korean and North Korean athletes marched into the stadium together carrying the [[Korean Unification Flag]] while \"Arirang\" played.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2000/09/16/olympics/two-koreas-make-history-during-opening-ceremony/|title=Two Koreas make history during opening ceremony|last=Ito|first=Makoto|date=2000-09-16|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n* South Korean fans used \"Arirang\" as a cheering song during the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n* South Korean [[Figure skating|figure skater]] [[Yuna Kim]] performed to \"Arirang\" during her [[Free skating|free skate]] in the [[2011 World Figure Skating Championships]], where she placed second.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/sports_globetrotting/2011/04/kim-ando-flatt-czisny-world-figure-skating.html|title=Botched jumps cost Kim world title, Czisny the bronze|last=Hersh|first=Philip|date=2011-04-30|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n* Parts of \"Arirang\" were used many times during the [[PyeongChang 2018]] Winter Olympics, especially during the Opening Ceremony<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/olimpiadas-de-inverno/videos/v/do-passado-ao-futuro-cerimonia-de-abertura-de-pyeongchang-projeta-futuro-de-criancas/6488926/|title=Do passado ao futuro cerimonia de abertura de pyeongchang projeta futuro de crian\u00e7as (In Portuguese)|date=2018-02-09|website=Sport TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227173340/http://sportv.globo.com/olimpiadas-de-inverno/videos/v/do-passado-ao-futuro-cerimonia-de-abertura-de-pyeongchang-projeta-futuro-de-criancas/6488926/|archive-date=2018-02-27|access-date=2018-02-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in the [[Olympic Broadcasting Services]] TV Intro. During the gala show of figure skating, [[Choi Da-bin]] skated to Arirang.\n*At the [[Korea at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] \"Arirang\" was played as the Korea Unification Team wins gold medal on [[canoeing]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/08/27/other_sports/1535394107_366201.html|title=Unified Korea dragon boat team win historic gold at Asian Games|last=AS|first=Diario|date=2018-08-27|work=AS.com|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n* D.Va's musical opening in [[Heroes of the Storm]] has elements of \"Arirang.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Warcraft Music and Gaming|title=D.Va Music (Dva Music) - Heroes of the Storm Music|date=2017-05-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nrQGi-WeNr8|accessdate=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n* Kim Wu's theme in [[Killer Instinct]] has elements of \"Arirang\", sung by Hoona Kim. <ref>{{Citation|last=Celldweller & Atlas Plug|title=Killer Instinct Season 3 - Creating The Music for \"Kim Wu\"|date=2016-03-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KPgk_dIcpzw|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|South Korea|Music}}\n*[[Arirang Mass Games]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}{{UNESCO Oral and Intangible music}}\n{{UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity/APA}}\n\n[[Category:Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity]]\n[[Category:Korean traditional music]]\n[[Category:Korean-language songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean folk songs]]\n[[Category:South Korea national football team songs]]\n[[Category:Korean traditions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Korean folk song}}\n{{About|the Korean traditional song}}\n{{Infobox intangible heritage\n| Image       = [[File:North Korea Victory Day 274 (9524347338).jpg|250px]]\n| Caption     = A man about to depart on a journey through a mountain pass is seen off by a woman in a scene from the [[Arirang Festival]] in [[North Korea]].\n| ICH         = Arirang in North Korea\n| State Party = North Korea\n| Type        = \n| Criteria    = \n| ID          = 914\n| Region      = APA\n| Year        = 2014\n| Session     = 9th\n| Danger      = \n| Link        = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/lists?RL=00914\n| Below       = \n| Note        = \n}}\n{{Infobox intangible heritage\n| Image       = [[File:Song So-Hee performing Arirang.jpg|250px]]\n| Caption     = [[Song So-hee]] performing \"Arirang\"\n| ICH         = Arirang in South Korea\n| State Party = South Korea\n| Type        = \n| Criteria    = \n| ID          = 445\n| Region      = APA\n| Year        = 2012\n| Session     = 7th\n| Danger      = \n| Link        = http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/lists?RL=00445\n| Below       = \n| Note        = \n}}\n\n\"'''Arirang'''\" ({{lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791}}; {{IPA-ko|a.\u027ei.\u027ea\u014b|}}) is a [[Koreans|Korean]] [[Folk music|folk song]] that is often considered to be the [[anthem]] of [[Korea]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2014/11/27/39/0701000000AEN20141127000300315F.html|title=N. Korea's Arirang wins UNESCO intangible heritage status|date=2014-11-27|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2017-12-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206005934/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2014/11/27/39/0701000000AEN20141127000300315F.html|archive-date=2017-12-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> There are about 3,600 variations of 60 different versions of the song, all of which include a refrain similar to, \"Arirang, arirang, arariyo ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694}})\"<ref name=\":2\" /> It is estimated the song is more than 600 years old.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/03/317_126329.html|title='Arirang' makes it to UNESCO heritage|last=Chung|first=Ah-young|date=2012-12-12|newspaper=The Korea Times|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n\"Arirang\" is included twice on the [[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] list. [[South Korea]] successfully submitted the song for inclusion on the UNESCO list in 2012.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?lg=en&pg=00011&RL=00445|title=Arirang, lyrical folk song in the Republic of Korea|work=Intangible Cultural Heritage|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref> [[North Korea]] also successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?lg=en&pg=00011&RL=00914|title=Arirang folk song in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|website=Intangible Cultural Heritage|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref> In 2015, the [[South Korea]]n [[Cultural Heritage Administration]] added the song to its list of important intangible cultural assets.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2015/07/15/2015071501147.html|title='Arirang' Listed as National Intangible Asset|date=2015-07-15|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=2017-12-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nthe song is sung today in both North and South Korea, a symbol of unity in an otherwise divided country, since the Korean war.\n\n==History==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2017}}\n\n===Origin===\nIt is believed that \"Arirang\" originated in [[Jeongseon County|Jeongseon]], [[Gangwon Province, South Korea|Gangwon Province]]. According to a legend, the name is derived from the story of a bachelor and a maiden who fell in love while picking [[Camellia]] blossoms near the wharf at Auraji ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\uc6b0\ub77c\uc9c0}}). There are two versions of this story. In the first one, the bachelor cannot cross the Auraji to meet the maiden because the water is too high and so, they sing a song to express their sorrow. In the second version, the bachelor attempts to cross the Auraji and drowns, singing the sorrowful song after he dies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DsR3BgAAQBAJ|title=Encyclopedia of Korean Folk Literature|last=The National Folk Museum of Korea|publisher=\uae38\uc7a1\uc774\ubbf8\ub514\uc5b4|year=2014|isbn=978-8928900848|volume=Encyclopedia of Korean Folklore and Traditional Culture Vol. III|location=|pages=95\u201396}}</ref>\n\nOther theories on the origin of the name \"Arirang\" point to [[Lady Aryeong]], wife of the first king of [[Silla]]; \"arin,\" the [[Jurchen language|Jurchen]] word for \"hometown\".\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/08/135_126317.html|title=From lyrical folk song to cheering song: variations of 'Arirang' in Korean history|date=2012-12-06|work=The Korea Times|access-date=2017-12-06|agency=Yonhap News Agency|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to {{nowrap|Prof. Keith Howard}}, \"Arirang\" originated in the mountainous regions of [[Jeongseon]] and the first mention of the song was found in a 1756 manuscript.<ref name=\"Howard2017\">{{cite book|author=Keith Howard|title=Perspectives on Korean Music: Preserving Korean Music: Intangible Cultural Properties as Icons of Identity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LgskDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT108|date=15 May 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-91168-9|volume=I}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Pete Seeger, who sang the song in concert in the 1960s, the song goes back to the 1600s when a despotic emperor was imprisoning people right and left who had opposed him. He hung these prisoners from tall pine trees on top of the hill of Arirang, located outside Seoul. Legend states that one of the prisoners condemned to death, walked his final miles singing of how much he loved his country, and how much he hated to say goodbye to it. It was soon picked up by the other prisoners, where it became a Korean tradition that any man had the right to sing this song before his execution.\n\n===First recording===\nThe first known recording of \"Arirang\" was made in 1896 by American [[Ethnology|ethnologist]] [[Alice Cunningham Fletcher|Alice C. Fletcher]]. At her home in [[Washington, D.C.]], Fletcher recorded three Korean students singing a song she called \"Love Song: Ar-ra-rang.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170927000618|title=Oldest recorded Arirang to be on display in Seoul|last=Yoon|first=Min-sik|date=2017-09-27|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/culturesports/2012/05/04/25/0701000000AEN20120504002500315F.HTML|title=Arirang under renewed light ahead of UNESCO application|last=Kim|first=Hyeh-won|date=2012-05-11|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> One source suggests that the students belonged to noble Korean families and were studying abroad at [[Howard University]] during the period in which the recording was made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ikorea.ac.kr/File/intro/Fletcherpreliminaryarticle.pdf|title=Alice Fletcher's Notes on the Earliest Recordings of Korean Music|last=Provine|first=Robert C.|work=The Academy of Korean Studies|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> The recordings are currently housed in the U.S. [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lccn.loc.gov/2015655305|title=Alice C Fletcher collection of Korean cylinder recordings|website=Library of Congress|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n===Resistance anthem===\nDuring the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese occupation of Korea]] from 1910 to 1945, when singing was proscribed and it became a criminal offense for anyone to be singing any patriotic song including the national anthem of Korea, Arirang became an unofficial anthem. \"Arirang\" became a resistance anthem against [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] rule.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Atkins|first=E. Taylor|date=August 2007|title=The Dual Career of \"Arirang\": The Korean Resistance Anthem That Became a Japanese Pop Hit|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=66|issue=3|pages=645\u2013687|lay-url=|jstor=20203201|doi=10.1017/s0021911807000927|url=http://commons.lib.niu.edu/handle/10843/13185}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WhZRCgAAQBAJ&dq|title=Traditional Music: Sounds in Harmony with Nature|last=Koehler|first=Robert|publisher=Seoul Selection|year=2015|isbn=978-1624120428|series=Volume 8 of Korea Essentials|location=|pages=}}</ref> Korean protesters sang \"Arirang\" during the [[March 1st Movement|March 1 Movement]], a Korean demonstration against the Japanese Empire in 1919. Many of the variations of \"Arirang\" that were written during the occupation contain themes of injustice, the plight of labourers, and guerrilla warfare. It was also sung by the mountain guerrillas who were fighting against the fascists. <ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe most well-known lyrics to \"Arirang\" first appeared in the 1926 [[silent film]] ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]],'' directed by [[Na Woon-gyu]]. ''Arirang'' is now considered a [[lost film]] but various accounts say the film was about a Korean student who became mentally ill after being imprisoned and tortured by the Japanese. The film was a hit upon its release and is considered the first Korean nationalist film.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Film Out of Bounds: Essays and Interviews on Non-Mainstream Cinema Worldwide|last=Edwards|first=Matthew|publisher=McFarland|year=2014|isbn=978-1476607801|location=|pages=198}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Divine Work, Japanese Colonial Cinema and its Legacy|last=Taylor-Jones|first=Kate|publisher=Bloomsbury USA|year=2017|isbn=978-1501306136|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity in Japan===\nDuring the Japanese occupation of Korea, Japan experienced a craze for Korean culture and for \"Arirang\", in particular. Over 50 Japanese versions of \"Arirang\" were released between 1931 and 1943, in genres including [[Pop music|pop]], [[jazz]], and [[Mambo (music)|mambo]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Some of the former Japanese Imperial soldiers remember and sing \"Arirang\" from the memories they recollect from their service in [[Japanese Korea]], or from the Korean [[comfort women]] (sex slaves) or the Korean forcefully-inscripted labourers and soldiers.\n\n===Musical score===\n<score vorbis=\"1\">\n\\relative c' { \\key f \\major \\time 9/8 \\tempo \"Lento\" 4 = 140 \\set Staff.midiInstrument = #\"violin\"\nc4. ~ c4 d8  c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4. g8 a g f4 ( d8 ) | c4. ~ ( c4 d8 c d ) r8 |\\break\nf4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4 ( g8 ) f4 ( d8 ) c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8 f4.| f4. ~ f4. r4. |\\break\nc'4. ~ c c | c4. a4. g4. | a4. g4 a8 f4 ( d8 ) | c4. ~ ( c4  d8 c d ) r8 |\\break\nf4. ~ f4 g8  f4 ( g8 ) | a4 ( g8 ) f4 ( d8 ) c4 ( d8 ) | f4. ~ f4 g8 f4.| f4. ~ f4. r4. \\bar \"|.\"}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\ub098 \ub97c \ubc84 \ub9ac \uace0 \uac00 \uc2dc \ub294 \ub2d8 \uc740\n\uc2ed \ub9ac \ub3c4 \ubabb \uac00 \uc11c \ubc1c \ubcd1 \ub09c \ub2e4}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\uccad \ucc9c \ud558 \ub298 \uc5d4 \ubcc4 \ub3c4 - \ub9ce \uace0\n\uc6b0 \ub9ac \ub124 \uac00 \uc2b4 \uc5d4 \uafc8 \ub3c4 \ub9ce \ub2e4}\n\\addlyrics {\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uc544 \ub77c - - \ub9ac \uc694\n\uc544 \ub9ac \ub791 \uace0 \uac1c \ub85c \ub118 \uc5b4 \uac04 \ub2e4\n\uc800 \uae30 \uc800 \uc0b0 \uc774 \ubc31 \ub450 \uc0b0 \uc774\ub77c \uc9c0\n\ub3d9 \uc9c0 \uc123 \ub2ec \uc5d0 \ub3c4 \uaf43 \ub9cc \ud540 \ub2e4}\n</score>\n\n==Lyrics==\nAll versions of \"Arirang\" include a [[refrain]] similar to, \"Arirang, arirang, arariyo ({{Lang|ko|\uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694}}).\"<ref name=\":2\" /> The word \"arirang\" itself is nonsensical and does not have a precise meaning in [[Korean language|Korean]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/arirang.php|title=Arirang (\uc544\ub9ac\ub791)|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> While the other lyrics vary from version to version, the themes of sorrow, separation, reunion, and love appear in most versions.<ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQkyBgAAQBAJ|title=Two Lenses on the Korean Ethos: Key Cultural Concepts and Their Appearance in Cinema|last=Kim Yoon|first=Keumsil|last2=Williams|first2=Bruce|publisher=McFarland|year=2015|isbn=978-0786496822|location=|pages=39}}</ref>\n\nThe table below includes the lyrics of \"Standard Arirang\" from [[Seoul]]. The first two lines are the refrain. The refrain is followed by three [[Verse (music)|verses]].\n\n{|\n|\n: '''Korean'''\n|\n: '''Romanization'''\n|\n: '''English translation'''<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Damodaran|first=Ramu|date=Winter 2017|title=UNAI Impacts Scholarship, Research for Greater Good|url=|journal=SangSaeng|publisher=APCEIU|volume=49|pages=23|via=}}</ref>\n|-\n|\n: \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub9ac\ub791, \uc544\ub77c\ub9ac\uc694...\n: \uc544\ub9ac\ub791 \uace0\uac1c\ub85c \ub118\uc5b4\uac04\ub2e4.\n|\n: Arirang, Arirang, Arariyo...\n: Arirang gogaero neomeoganda.\n|\n: Arirang, Arirang, Arariyo...\n: You are going over Arirang hill.\n|-\n|\n: \ub098\ub97c \ubc84\ub9ac\uace0 \uac00\uc2dc\ub294 \ub2d8\uc740\n: \uc2ed\ub9ac\ub3c4 \ubabb\uac00\uc11c \ubc1c\ubcd1\ub09c\ub2e4.\n|\n: Nareul beorigo gasineun nimeun\n: Sibrido mosgaseo balbyeongnanda.\n|\n: My love, you are leaving me\n: Your feet will be sore before you go ten [[Li (unit)|''ri'']].\n|-\n|\n: \uccad\ucc9c\ud558\ub298\uc5d4 \uc794\ubcc4\ub3c4 \ub9ce\uace0,\n: \uc6b0\ub9ac\ub124 \uac00\uc2b4\uc5d4 \ud76c\ub9dd\ub3c4 \ub9ce\ub2e4.\n|\n: Cheongcheonhaneuren janbyeoldo manko,\n: Urine gaseumen huimangdo manda.\n|\n: Just as there are many stars in the clear sky,\n: There are also many dreams in our heart.\n|-\n|\n: \uc800\uae30 \uc800 \uc0b0\uc774 \ubc31\ub450\uc0b0\uc774\ub77c\uc9c0,\n: \ub3d9\uc9c0 \uc123\ub2ec\uc5d0\ub3c4 \uaf43\ub9cc \ud540\ub2e4.\n|\n: Jeogi jeo sani Baekdusaniraji,\n: Dongji seotdaredo kkotman pinda.\n|\n: There, over there, that mountain is [[Baekdu Mountain]],\n: Where, even in the middle of winter days, flowers bloom.\n|}\n\n==Variations==\nThere are an estimated 3,600 variations of 60 different versions of \"Arirang.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Titles of different versions of \"Arirang\" are usually prefixed by their place of origin.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWhile \"[[Jeongseon County|Jeongseon]] Arirang\" is generally considered to be the original version of the song, \"Bonjo Arirang\" (literally: Standard Arirang) from [[Seoul]] is one of the most famous versions. This version was first made popular when it was used as the theme song of the influential 1926 film ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOther famous variations include \"Jindo Arirang\" from [[South Jeolla]] Province, a region known for being the birthplace of Korean folk music genres [[pansori]] and [[sinawi]]; and \"[[Miryang]] Arirang\" from [[South Gyeongsang]] Province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/jindo.php|title=Jindo Arirang|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sejongculturalsociety.org/composition/current/music/milyang.php|title=Milyang Arirang|date=2015|website=Sejong Cultural Society|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n==Official status==\n[[File:Arirang (USAS).ogg|thumb|right|Arirang performed by the [[United States Army Band]] Strings with a tenor soloist]]\n\n===UNESCO===\nBoth [[South Korea]] and [[North Korea]] submitted \"Arirang\" to be included on the [[UNESCO]] [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] list. South Korea successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2012.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> North Korea successfully submitted the song for inclusion in 2014.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DPRK_Arirang\" />\n\n===South Korea===\nIn 2015, the South Korean [[Cultural Heritage Administration]] added the \"Arirang\" to its list of important intangible cultural assets.<ref name=\":5\" />[[File:Arirang.ogg|thumb|right|Arirang performed by the [[United States Army Band]] Chorus with a tenor soloist]]\n\n===U.S. Army===\n[[File:Arirang,_Lyrics_in_English_Adaptation-2_by_GSIT_at_HUFS_in_2013,_sung_by_HUFS_students.ogg|thumb|right|Arirang, Lyrics in English Adaptation-2 by GSIT at HUFS in 2013. Adaptation of [[W. B. Yeats]]' poem, \"The Falling of the Leaves,\" into the Arirang melody to convey the woe and sorrow with which Korean people sympathize when listening to the song.]]\nThe [[United States Army|U.S. Army's]] [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]] adopted \"Arirang\" as its official march song in May 1956, after receiving permission from [[Syngman Rhee]], the first president of South Korea. The division had been stationed in Korea from 1950 to 1953, during the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.7ida.us/history.asp|title=Chronological History 7th Infantry Division|date=2012-05-25|website=7th Infantry Division Association|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|section|date=October 2018}}\n\n===Music===\n* American composer [[John Barnes Chance]] based his 1962-63 [[concert band]] composition ''[[Variations on a Korean Folk Song]]'' on a version of \"Arirang\" that he heard in Korea in the late 1950s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Teaching Music Through Performing in Band Volume 1|last=Blocher, Cramer, Migliaro Corporon, Lautzenheiser, Lisk, Miles|publisher=GIA Publications, Inc.|year=2010|isbn=|location=Chicago|pages=590\u2013598}}</ref>\n\nPete Seeger sang the song, with an English translation in a concert in the 1960s.\n\n* The tune of \"Arirang\" is used for the 1986 Christian hymn, \"Christ, You Are the Fullness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hymnary.org/text/christ_you_are_the_fullness|title=Christ, You Are the Fullness|website=Hymnary|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n* The [[New York Philharmonic]] performed \"Arirang\" for an encore during [[2008 New York Philharmonic visit to North Korea|its trip to North Korea]] on February 26, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/world/asia/27symphony.html|title=North Koreans Welcome Symphonic Diplomacy|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=2008-02-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* In November 2013, the student choir at [[Hankuk University of Foreign Studies]] performed \"Arirang\" in English, Chinese, Japanese, French, Italian, Spanish, German, Russian, Arabic and Korean.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20131119001011|title=HUFS to hold concert featuring 'Arirang' in 10 languages|last=Lee|first=Claire|date=2013-11-19|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[K-pop]] group [[BTS (band)|BTS]] performed an \"Arirang\" medley at [[KCON (music festival)|KCON]] France in June 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=Mnet K-POP|title=[KCON 2016 France\u00d7M COUNTDOWN] Opening Performance _ Arirang Medley(\uc544\ub9ac\ub791 \uc5f0\uace1) M COUNTDOWN 160614 EP.47|date=2016-06-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vwc5zTayVJw|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref>\n* An October 2016 episode of South Korean TV music competition show ''[[Immortal Songs: Singing the Legend]]'' was an \"Arirang\" special, featuring famous musicians performing different variations of the song.<ref>{{Citation|last=KBS World TV|title=Immortal Songs 2 {{!}} \ubd88\ud6c4\uc758 \uba85\uace1 2: \"Arirang\" special [ENG/2016.10.29]|date=2016-10-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vXVwekhWne0|accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref>\n* On June 12, 2018, a Slovenian avant-garde music group [[Laibach]] marked the historic summit in [[Singapore]] between President [[Donald Trump]] and the leader of [[North Korea]], [[Kim Jong-un]], by sharing a track dedicated to the  [[Korean reunification]] process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w_PCdJ3Dn9E|title=Laibach - Arirang (Official Audio)|last=YouTube|date=2018-06-12|work=Mute Records|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\n* ''[[Arirang (1926 film)|Arirang]]'' is the title of early Korean filmmaker [[Na Woon-gyu]]'s influential 1926 film, which popularized the song \"Arirang\" in the 20th century.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* ''[[Arirang (2011 film)|Arirang]]'' is also the title of a 2011 South Korean documentary. The film won the top prize in the [[Un Certain Regard]] category at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jun/07/arirang-review|title=Arirang \u2013 review|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|date=2012-06-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n* [[Arirang (TV network)|Arirang TV]] and [[Arirang Radio]] are international English-language media stations run by the [[Korea International Broadcasting Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2011/04/113_86027.html|title=Arirang TV begins DTV service in metropolitan Washington, D.C., area|date=2011-04-28|work=The Korea Times|access-date=2017-12-08|agency=Yonhap News Agency|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/01/11/2012011101582.html|title=Arirang Radio to Go On Air in U.S.|date=2012-01-11|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en}}</ref>\n* Arirang will appear in the [[Gardens by the Bay]] Musical Lighting in [[Singapore]].\n\n===Sports===\n* North Korea's mass gymnastics and performance festival is commonly known as the [[Arirang Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thediplomat.com/2013/07/pyongyangs-arirang-festival-eye-candy-for-the-masses/|title=Pyongyang's Arirang Festival: Eye Candy for the Masses|last=DeHart|first=Jonathan|date=2013-07-29|work=The Diplomat|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* At the [[2000 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]] in [[Sydney|Sydney, Australia]], South Korean and North Korean athletes marched into the stadium together carrying the [[Korean Unification Flag]] while \"Arirang\" played.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2000/09/16/olympics/two-koreas-make-history-during-opening-ceremony/|title=Two Koreas make history during opening ceremony|last=Ito|first=Makoto|date=2000-09-16|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=2017-12-08|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n* South Korean fans used \"Arirang\" as a cheering song during the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n* South Korean [[Figure skating|figure skater]] [[Yuna Kim]] performed to \"Arirang\" during her [[Free skating|free skate]] in the [[2011 World Figure Skating Championships]], where she placed second.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/sports_globetrotting/2011/04/kim-ando-flatt-czisny-world-figure-skating.html|title=Botched jumps cost Kim world title, Czisny the bronze|last=Hersh|first=Philip|date=2011-04-30|website=Chicago Tribune|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n* Parts of \"Arirang\" were used many times during the [[PyeongChang 2018]] Winter Olympics, especially during the Opening Ceremony<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/olimpiadas-de-inverno/videos/v/do-passado-ao-futuro-cerimonia-de-abertura-de-pyeongchang-projeta-futuro-de-criancas/6488926/|title=Do passado ao futuro cerimonia de abertura de pyeongchang projeta futuro de crian\u00e7as (In Portuguese)|date=2018-02-09|website=Sport TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227173340/http://sportv.globo.com/olimpiadas-de-inverno/videos/v/do-passado-ao-futuro-cerimonia-de-abertura-de-pyeongchang-projeta-futuro-de-criancas/6488926/|archive-date=2018-02-27|access-date=2018-02-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in the [[Olympic Broadcasting Services]] TV Intro. During the gala show of figure skating, [[Choi Da-bin]] skated to Arirang.\n*At the [[Korea at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] \"Arirang\" was played as the Korea Unification Team wins gold medal on [[canoeing]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/08/27/other_sports/1535394107_366201.html|title=Unified Korea dragon boat team win historic gold at Asian Games|last=AS|first=Diario|date=2018-08-27|work=AS.com|access-date=2018-08-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n* D.Va's musical opening in [[Heroes of the Storm]] has elements of \"Arirang.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Warcraft Music and Gaming|title=D.Va Music (Dva Music) - Heroes of the Storm Music|date=2017-05-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nrQGi-WeNr8|accessdate=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n* Kim Wu's theme in [[Killer Instinct]] has elements of \"Arirang\", sung by Hoona Kim. <ref>{{Citation|last=Celldweller & Atlas Plug|title=Killer Instinct Season 3 - Creating The Music for \"Kim Wu\"|date=2016-03-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KPgk_dIcpzw|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|South Korea|Music}}\n*[[Arirang Mass Games]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}{{UNESCO Oral and Intangible music}}\n{{UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity/APA}}\n\n[[Category:Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity]]\n[[Category:Korean traditional music]]\n[[Category:Korean-language songs]]\n[[Category:National symbols of Korea]]\n[[Category:South Korean folk songs]]\n[[Category:South Korea national football team songs]]\n[[Category:Korean traditions]]\n", "name_user": "Cathal \u00d3 h\u00c9anna", "label": "safe", "comment": "Capitalisation of the start of a sentence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arirang"}
